AUTHORITIES are still searching for a 19-year-old man who went missing while swimming with his friends at Blythedale Beach on the north coast of KwaZulu-Natal yesterday.Police provincial police spokesperson Lieutenant-Colonel Nqobile Gwala told The Mercury yesterday that the search for the 19-year-old man is continuing.IPSS Medical Rescue said the man was presumed drowned.IPSS spokesperson Paul Herbst said shortly after 6pm on Saturday evening, IPSS Medical Rescue Search and Rescue division, together with SAPS Search and Rescue and KwaDukuza Municipality lifeguards, responded to reports of a drowning at a Blythedale Beach.“Upon arrival of personnel, witness reports indicated that a teenager had entered the sea with friends after lifeguards had gone off duty. He reportedly got into difficulty before disappearing from sight,” he said.MORE ON THISTwo people drowned by abnormally high waves after Tonga volcanoSearch and rescue efforts continue for 15-year old Gqeberha teen who went missing whilst surfing.Young sisters rushed to hospital after being rescued from near-drowning in uMdlotiConcern for water safety as drownings dampen the new year funHerbst said rescue crews conducted extensive searches.“Unfortunately no positive results were achieved and the search was suspended due to loss of light,” he said.Search efforts recommenced at daylight yesterday morning.Meanwhile, in a separate incident Reaction Unit South Africa (Rusa) spokesperson Prem Balram said a 46-year-old man was rescued by lifeguards after he experienced difficulty while attempting to assist a relative at uMdloti Beach on Saturday.Balram said they received four calls from the public reporting two people drowning near the tidal pool.He said officers and medics were immediately dispatched.“Rusa members arrived on scene at approximately 11.49am and confirmed that the bather had been rescued by lifeguards,”he said.Balram said according to the man’s family, he had noticed his nephew experiencing difficulty in the water and he went in to his rescue.“His nephew grabbed on to him when he started experiencing difficulty. Lifeguards managed to safely retrieve him from the surf. His relative made his way out of the water without assistance,” he said.Balram added that medics examined the fatigued swimmer; however, he declined further medical assistance.MAN rescued while attempting to save his nephew at uMdloti beach.  |  Reaction Unit South Africa.THE MERCURY